feedback: Enjoyable. Made me feel like I'm fairly safe about choosing safe sites but not very knowlegdable about the details of it all.

I don't like being asked for personal information that really has nothing to do with the platform that I'm signing into. But companies still want to gather such information and holds my membership at ransom unless I provide the information.  Companies should be banned from asking for unwarranted information.

After working in an accounting firm and learning most of the phishing red flags, I don't think it's a very concerning issue for me personally but it's dangerous for other people - especially elder ones who might not understand technology as well

This was a well put together survey. It made me realize that the confidence I have in myself when it comes to my online and professional security can be somewhat relaxed, due to me believing I know what to spot and how to avoid it. However this can also blind me into a false sense of security.

Question 24 is rather ambiguous. Is it asked to be answered given the experimental trial (which revealed the website to be fake) to test whether the respondent has learnt from his/her mistakes? Asked to make sure the responses are internally valid, or asked in reference to the actual government COVID-19 website (into which there really is no point in signing in)? The familiarity question could have used some statements corresponding to each response-something like "I am familiar with this websites existence but not much more" for "somewhat familiar" to elicit answers which most accurately affect the respondents familiarity. The time taken for the experimental trial is largely dependent on the ease of finding where the login button is. So a longer time taken may not indicate a longer time deliberating over whether the website is phishing but rather trying to locate the login button. Also this response bar/text box or whatever is really small which is annoying. Nice experiment and survey though. Would be interesting to see the results by demography.
